<main>
  <h1><span class="cfg" id="cfgprefix">~/.claude/</span>config</h1>
  <p class="sub">Skills, commands, agents, and config files — versioned here, symlinked into the Claude config dir. Collections (like <b>work/</b>, gitignored) mirror the same shape and merge in automatically. Everything is plain files: review &amp; commit with git as usual.</p>
  <details id="links" open>
    <summary>links <span id="linksum"></span></summary>
    <div id="linkrows"></div>
    <div class="cfgdir" id="cfgrow"></div>
    <div class="cfgdir hint" id="cfghint"></div>
  </details>
  <details id="help">
    <summary>how this works</summary>
    <div class="helpbody">
      <p><b>The repo is the source of truth; the config dir just points at it.</b>
      Claude Code reads one config dir (<code>~/.claude</code> by default). The links
      panel symlinks each piece of it — skills, commands, agents, output-styles,
      CLAUDE.md, settings.json, keybindings.json — to files in this repo, so your
      real config lives in git and a <code>git pull</code> updates every machine.</p>
      <p><b>Importing an existing config:</b> setting "config dir" to a path does
      NOT import anything by itself — it only chooses where the symlinks are
      managed. But when a row shows "real", clicking <b>link</b> takes over that
      content: if the repo side doesn't exist yet it is <i>adopted</i> (moved into
      the repo, then symlinked back — commit it after); if the repo side already
      exists, the old content is renamed to <code>*.bak</code> next to it and the
      link replaces it. Alternatively, <b>⇪ folder</b>-upload any config-shaped
      directory (containing skills/, commands/, CLAUDE.md, ...) to import it as a
      <i>collection</i> without touching your live config.</p>
      <p><b>Collections</b> are extra config sets at the repo root (e.g.
      <code>work/</code>). Their skills/commands/agents/output-styles merge into the
      live config automatically via generated symlinks (a collection command runs as
      <code>/&lt;collection&gt;:&lt;name&gt;</code>; a collection skill loads as
      <code>&lt;collection&gt;-&lt;name&gt;</code>). Config files can't merge — Claude
      Code reads exactly one CLAUDE.md / settings.json — so each file row has a
      <i>source</i> dropdown choosing which copy is linked on this machine.
      <code>work/</code> is gitignored: private, one folder, never committed.</p>
      <p><b>MCP servers</b> are different: Claude Code stores user-scope servers in
      <code>~/.claude.json</code> (machine state, NOT inside the config dir, and not
      affected by the config-dir setting). The mcp tab keeps server definitions
      versioned in the repo (<code>claude/mcp-servers.json</code> or a collection's
      copy) and <b>applies</b> them into <code>~/.claude.json</code> per machine;
      machine-only servers can be adopted into the repo or removed.</p>
      <p><b>Limitations:</b> a non-default config dir only takes effect if you
      <code>export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=...</code> in your shell — the UI can't do that
      for you. Claude Code reads settings/CLAUDE.md at session start, so changes
      apply to new sessions. Skills must be direct children of the skills dir
      (that's why nested folders get generated links). Moving a skill into a
      folder renames it (<code>tdd</code> → <code>ai-tdd</code>). Nothing here
      touches project-level config (<code>.claude/</code>, <code>.mcp.json</code>
      inside your projects). This page runs locally from your clone and edits
      plain files — it never commits; review with git as usual.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
